    "## Question: Is there a real relationship between what product category someone buys and their gender, or does any pattern in the counts just look different by chance?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "70794a58",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.009438,
     "end_time": "2026-07-13T11:53:48.599674+00:00",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2026-07-13T11:53:48.590236+00:00",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "1. H0 (null hypothesis): Product_Category and Gender are independent — knowing someone's gender tells you nothing about which category they're likely to buy. Any differences in the counts are just random sampling noise.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. H1 (alternative hypothesis): Product_Category and Gender are associated — gender does relate to category preference in some real way."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0dcd750d",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.009921,
     "end_time": "2026-07-13T11:53:48.619170+00:00",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2026-07-13T11:53:48.609249+00:00",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "Both Product Category and Gender are categorical, not numeric — so this is not a t-test/ANOVA situation at all. The right tool here is the chi-square test of independence."
   ]
  },
